#3313
The Formation System~
   &w Heroes of Icewind Dale uses a formation combat system.  This allows for up
to 9 individuals to be in combat per party/group.  The formations are split into
3 rows of three, numbered 1-3, 4-6 and 7-9.  Party members in slots 1-3 are the
tanks, and they take the brunt of the damage.  They are able to attack with any
kind of weapon, though attacking with ranged weapons without the point blank
shot feat will result in attacks of oppourtunity and penalties to hit.  In rows
4-6 members may use spears, polearms and ranged weapons.  In the final row,
slots 7-9, members may only use ranged weapons.  In any slot a character may
cast a spell, though touch attacks obviously require that the member be in the
front row to make the touch.  Likewise if a caster casts a spell in the front
row they open themselves to a free attack while they cast the spell.  Mobs, in a
similar manner, attack in rows when fighting more than more.  If there are more
than 9 characters in a group, only 9 of them may participate in combat.  The
others can feel free to assist with spells (not offensive ones), magic items,
skill use, or what have you.  To assign someone, or yourself to a position type
reform <character name / mob keyword> <formation slot (1-9)>.  So if I wanted to
set myself to position 6, which is the right side of the middle row, I would
type 'reform me 6'.  Only the party leader has the ability to reform someone
else.  It is often a good idea for the party leader to thus be someone who
either works in one of the two back rows, so they can spend their time adjusting
formation instead of controlling hate.  Fighters generally make the best party
leaders since usually they don't have much extra to do during combat if they
aren't controlling hate besides repeatedly use their weapon, which is performed
automatically.  To view the current formation simply type 'form'.  Please go
east and read up on the hate system and how to manage hate against your
character or party.  &n
